Text.name: ve8898
Text.label: Cost Overview Information Text
Text.description: Text box containing information about the Cost Overview page.

P.Span: This section shows annualtrends in warrantycosts. Where do you see the biggest issues?
The button barallows you to filter the report by ship year.
The key value metrics provide a quick view of warranty costs for the specified ship year.

Span.Span: This bar chart compares the different costs for each Primary Labor Group. Drill down into Primary Labor Codes. Does one Primary Labor Code stand out more than the others? This chart is also linked to Cost Details which provides detailed informationon total and average costs. The sparkline shows you how the total warranty costs have changed over time. Which model(s) have the most expense?
Total Warranty Cost Change from Previous Year:
This bubble plot shows how the labor costs (x-axis), material costs (y-axis) and the total warranty costs (size of the bubble) have changed from the previous year.

Text.name: ve11305
Text.label: Detailed Cost Analysis More Information
Text.description: This text box provides information about the Detailed Cost Analysis page.

Span.Span: This section offers a more granular view by car make, model and model year. Select
to open the prompt container. Notice how the charts change as you modify the filters formake, model and model year.

P.Span: The buttonbar filters the charts by ship year.
Labor and Material Costs by Labor Code:

This chart breaks out Labor Costs (color) vs Material Costs (size) by Labor Group. Drill into any Primary Labor Description to see details about Primary Labor Codes. This chart also filters the step plot. To see details about any of these labor codes use the page link to Detailed Cost Analysis by Product Unit IDs.
Costs by Claim Submitted Date:
This step plotshows how the Gross Claim Amount is trending over time based on claim submitteddate.
Use the page link to Detailed Cost Analysis by Product Unit IDsin the Labor and Material Costs by Labor Code treemap
. Entera number for the Number of Product Unit Id's to return in the table. This table provides additional details such as the actual VIN andwhere it was manufactured.

Span.Span: Now select Prompts and use the drop down menusto filter the report. The first filter, Make, filters the report and the other two dropdown menus. The next filter, Product Model, filters the report and the Model Year menu beside it. The Model Year dropdown will also filter the report. You can use these filters individually or together. Choose
as the product model. Drill down on
. Notice that the step chart has a rapid increase in Labor costs. From

in the treemap select the Page Link to Detailed Cost Analysis by Product Unit IDs. Enter 5 in the box. Notice the one really high labor cost and the part that was replaced. We may need to investigate this further to see if better training or additional tools might prevent the high labor cost.

Text.name: ve13609
Text.label: Labor Group Analysis Information Text
Text.description: This text box contains information about the Labor Group Analysis and Forecast page.

P.Span: This section provides a snapshot of total claims by Labor Group and cost forecasts. The forecast helps project future expenditures, which makes planning more accurate.
Total Claim Count by Primary Labor Group (all years):

This pie chart shows the percent breakdown of the number of claims for each primary labor group for all years. Notice that the highest number of warranty claims comes from Chasis and Transmission labor groups. The Transmission claims may not make up the majority of warranty expenses cost-wise butthey do affect quite a few customers. This could lead to dissatisfied customers and a drop in customer loyalty.
Forecasts:

Span.Span: There are three different forecast charts for each primary labor group. Use the pie chart to filter the forecasts by primary labor group. Use the buttons at the bottom of the section to move between the forecasts for Total Claim Count, Gross Material Amount and Gross Labor Amount. These forecasts were created quickly and easily. In addition, the software automatically chooses the best model for each metric. Select the maximize button located in the top right corner. Results at located at the bottom of the Forecast image. Select

and you will see that the software chose a Seasonal Exponential Smoothing algorithm to create the forecasts for the Gross Material Amount and Gross Labor Amount. However, for the Total Claim Amount, the Winter's Method (multiplicative) algorithm was found to be a better fit.

Text.name: ve13532
Text.label: Labor Details Information Text
Text.description: This text box provides information about the Labor Details page.

P.Span: This section shows a more granular view into the labor code's costs and frequency. This section also breaks the information out by repairing dealer (see Gross Labor Amounts by Repairing Dealer chart).
Labor Description by Claim Amount:

This word cloud shows the Gross Claim Amount (size of font) and Total Claim Count(color) for the top Labor Code descriptions. Select a description and note how all the other charts change based on your selection. Do you notice any trends over time?
Labor Amounts by Repairing Dealer:

This dot plot shows theGross Labor Costs by repairing dealer. This chart is filtered by labor code descriptions when a description is selected in the Labor Description by Claim Amount chart. Notice any outliers? Selectoutliers to find the dealer ID whose labor costs are above the norm.
Claim Amount and Total Count by Month:

This chart show the Gross Claim Amount (teal line) and the Total Claim Count (orange line) over time. You can filter this chart by labor code description by selecting a description in the Labor Description by Claim Amount chart. Notice any trends? If you see an upward trend over time, you should investigate further.
Now check out the forecasts by going to the next section in the report: Labor Group Analysis and Forecast.
